@ARTICLE{noauthor_2013-sj,
  title     = "A Practical Guide to Measuring Social Structure Using Indirectly
               Observed Network Data",
  abstract  = "Aggregated relational data (ARD) are an increasingly common tool
               for learning about social networks through standard surveys.
               Recent statistical advances present social scientists with new
               options for analyzing such data. In this article, we propose
               guidelines for learning about various network processes using
               ARD and a template to aid practitioners. We first propose that
               ARD can be used to measure ?social distance? between a
               respondent and a subpopulation (individuals named Kevin, those
               in prison, or those serving in the military). We then present
               common methods for analyzing these data and associate each of
               these methods with a specific way of measuring social distance,
               thus associating statistical tools with their underlying social
